# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: linkerd
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:linkerd/2-features] Linkerd offers many features, outlined below.
[src:linkerd/2-features] For our walkthroughs and guides, please see the Linkerd task docs.
[src:linkerd/2-features] For a reference, see the Linkerd reference docs.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] Linkerd is a *service mesh* for Kubernetes.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] It makes running services easier and safer by giving you runtime debugging, observability, reliability, and security—all without requiring any changes to your code.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] For a brief introduction to the service mesh model, we recommend reading The Service Mesh: What Every Software Engineer Needs to Know about the World’s Most Over-Hyped Technology.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] Linkerd is fully open source, licensed under Apache v2, and is a Cloud Native Computing Foundation graduated project.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] Linkerd is developed in the open in the Linkerd GitHub organization.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] Linkerd has two basic components: a *control plane* and a *data plane*.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] Once Linkerd’s control plane has been installed on your Kubernetes cluster, you add the data plane to your workloads (called “meshing” or “injecting” your workloads) and voila!
[src:linkerd/2-overview] You can get started with Linkerd in minutes!
[src:linkerd/2-overview] Linkerd works by installing a set of ultralight, transparent “micro-proxies” next to each service instance.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] These proxies automatically handle all traffic to and from the service.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] Because they’re transparent, these proxies act as highly instrumented out-of-process network stacks, sending telemetry to, and receiving control signals from, the control plane.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] This design allows Linkerd to measure and manipulate traffic to and from your service without introducing excessive latency.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] In order to be as small, lightweight, and safe as possible, Linkerd’s micro-proxies are written in Rust and specialized for Linkerd.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] Linkerd is available in a variety of packages and channels.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] See the Linkerd Releases page for details.
[src:linkerd/2-overview] Get started with Linkerd in minutes, or check out the architecture for more details on Linkerd’s components and how they all fit together.
[src:linkerd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] The **Cloud Native Computing Foundation** (**CNCF**) is a subsidiary of the Linux Foundation founded in 2015 to support cloud-native computing.
[src:linkerd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] It was announced alongside Kubernetes 1.0, an open source container cluster manager, which was contributed to the Linux Foundation by Google as a seed technology.
[src:linkerd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Founding members include Google, CoreOS, Mesosphere, Red Hat, Twitter, Huawei, Intel, RX-M, Cisco, IBM, Docker, Univa, and VMware.
[src:linkerd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Today, CNCF is supported by over 450 members.
[src:linkerd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] In August 2018 Google announced that it was handing over operational control of Kubernetes to the community.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] In this guide, we’ll walk you through how to install Linkerd into your Kubernetes cluster.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Then we’ll deploy a sample application to show off what Linkerd can do.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] This guide is designed to walk you through the basics of Linkerd.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] First, you’ll install the *CLI* (command-line interface) onto your local machine.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Using this CLI, you’ll then install the *control plane* onto your Kubernetes cluster.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Finally, you’ll “mesh” an application by adding Linkerd’s *data plane* to it.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] This page contains instructions using the latest edge release of Linkerd.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Before anything else, we need to ensure you have access to modern Kubernetes cluster and a functioning `kubectl` command on your local machine.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] (If you don’t already have a Kubernetes cluster, one easy option is to run one on your local machine.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] You should see output with both a `Client Version` and `Server Version` component.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Now that we have our cluster, we’ll install the Linkerd CLI and use it validate that your cluster is capable of hosting Linkerd.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] before you can proceed to the next step.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] If this is your first time running Linkerd, you will need to download the `linkerd` CLI onto your local machine.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] The CLI will allow you to interact with your Linkerd deployment.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] This will install the CLI for the latest *edge release* of Linkerd.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] You should see the CLI version, and also `Server version: unavailable`.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] This is because you haven’t installed the control plane on your cluster.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Make sure that your Linkerd version and Kubernetes version are compatible by checking Linkerd’s supported Kubernetes versions.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Several features in Linkerd are configured using CRDs from the Gateway API project, including authorization policy and dynamic request routing.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] In many Kubernetes clusters, these CRDs are already available, but if they aren’t, you will need to install it first.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Follow these instructions for determining if the Gateway API is installed or how to install it.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Kubernetes clusters can be configured in many different ways.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Before we can install the Linkerd control plane, we need to check and validate that everything is configured correctly.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] If there are any checks that do not pass, make sure to follow the provided links and fix those issues before proceeding.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Now that you have the CLI running locally and a cluster that is ready to go, it’s time to install Linkerd on your Kubernetes cluster.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] These commands generate Kubernetes manifests with all the core resources required for Linkerd (feel free to inspect this output if you’re curious).
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Piping these manifests into `kubectl apply` then instructs Kubernetes to add those resources to your cluster.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] The `install --crds` command installs Linkerd’s Custom Resource Definitions (CRDs), which must be installed first, while the `install` command installs the Linkerd control plane.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] or by using a marketplace install from your Kubernetes provider.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Depending on the speed of your cluster’s Internet connection, it may take a minute or two for the control plane to finish installing.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] However, it’s not doing anything just yet.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] To see Linkerd in action, we’re going to need an application.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Let’s install a demo application called *Emojivoto*.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Emojivoto is a simple standalone Kubernetes application that uses a mix of gRPC and HTTP calls to allow the user to vote on their favorite emojis.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] This command installs Emojivoto onto your cluster, but Linkerd hasn’t been activated on it yet—we’ll need to “mesh” the application before Linkerd can work its magic.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Before we mesh it, let’s take a look at Emojivoto in its natural state.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] We’ll do this by forwarding traffic to its `web-svc` service so that we can point our browser to it.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] You should see Emojivoto in all its glory.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] If you click around Emojivoto, you might notice that it’s a little broken!
[src:linkerd/getting-started] For example, if you try to vote for the **donut** emoji, you’ll get a 404 page.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Don’t worry, these errors are intentional.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] With Emoji installed and running, we’re ready to *mesh* it—that is, to add Linkerd’s data plane proxies to it.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] We can do this on a live application without downtime, thanks to Kubernetes’s rolling deploys.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] This command retrieves all of the deployments running in the `emojivoto` namespace, runs their manifests through `linkerd inject`, and then reapplies it to the cluster.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] As with `install`, `inject` is a pure text operation, meaning that you can inspect the input and output before you use it.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Once piped into `kubectl apply`, Kubernetes will execute a rolling deploy and update each pod with the data plane’s proxies.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] You’ve now added Linkerd to an application!
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Just as with the control plane, it’s possible to verify that everything is working the way it should on the data plane side.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] And, of course, you can visit http://localhost:8080 and once again see Emojivoto in all its meshed glory.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Perhaps that last step was a little unsatisfying.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] We’ve added Linkerd to Emojivoto, but there are no visible changes to the application!
[src:linkerd/getting-started] That is part of Linkerd’s design—it does its best not to interfere with a functioning application.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Let’s take a closer look at what Linkerd is actually doing.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] To do this, we’ll need to install an *extension*.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Linkerd’s core control plane is extremely minimal, so Linkerd ships with extensions that add non-critical but often useful functionality to Linkerd, including a variety of dashboards.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Let’s install the **viz** extension, which will install an on-cluster metric stack and dashboard.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] With the control plane and extensions installed and running, we’re now ready to explore Linkerd!
[src:linkerd/getting-started] For extra credit, see if you can find the live metrics for each Emojivoto component, and determine which one has a partial failure.
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Congratulations, you have joined the exalted ranks of Linkerd users!
[src:linkerd/getting-started] Above all else: welcome to the Linkerd community!
[src:linkerd/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:linkerd/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:linkerd/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:linkerd/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:linkerd/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:linkerd/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:linkerd/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:linkerd/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:linkerd/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:linkerd/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:linkerd/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:linkerd/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:linkerd/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:linkerd/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:linkerd/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:linkerd/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:linkerd/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:linkerd/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:linkerd/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:linkerd/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:linkerd/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:linkerd/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:linkerd/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:linkerd/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:linkerd/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:linkerd/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:linkerd/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:linkerd/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:linkerd/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:linkerd/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:linkerd/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:linkerd/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:linkerd/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:linkerd/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:linkerd/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:linkerd/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:linkerd/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:linkerd/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:linkerd/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:linkerd/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:linkerd/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:linkerd/service-mesh] In software architecture, a **service mesh** is a dedicated infrastructure layer for facilitating service-to-service communications between services or microservices using a proxy.
[src:linkerd/service-mesh] A dedicated communication layer can provide numerous benefits, such as providing observability into communications, providing secure connections, and automating retries and backoff for failed requests.
[src:linkerd/service-mesh] A service mesh consists of network proxies paired with each service in an application and a set of task-management processes.
[src:linkerd/service-mesh] The proxies are called the data plane and the management processes are called the control plane.
[src:linkerd/service-mesh] The data plane intercepts calls between different services and processes them; the control plane is the brain of the mesh that coordinates the behavior of proxies and provides APIs for operations and maintenance personnel to manipulate and observe the entire network.
[src:linkerd/service-mesh] The service mesh architecture is implemented by software products such as Istio, Cilium, Linkerd, Consul, AWS App Mesh, Kuma, Traefik Mesh, and Greymatter.io.
[src:linkerd/service-mesh] Many service meshes use the Envoy proxy on the data plane.
